📖 Gelato handbook / 🧭 Why we exist

Why we exist

Building a company is hard. Building an amazing company is really, really hard. If we are to work together effectively to build a world-class organisation, we must all know why Gelato exists, where we are going and how we can get there.

Mission – why we do what we do

We make global opportunity everyone’s business.
  • Reaching a global audience
  • Accessing global trade and ecommerce
  • Joining the mission to transform manufacturing
  • Levelling the ecommerce playing field
  • Network effect multiplier for small businesses
  • Making smarter and greener manufacturing the responsibility of every business
  • Enabling print producers to grow and prosper

Vision – where we’re going

To rethink production, for the benefit of people and the planet.

We are united by a determination to make traditional production a thing of the past. We believe it is critical that we rethink the way production works, and that local on demand production is the solution to the current unreliable, unsustainable and sometimes unethical supply chains.

We never want to lose sight of who we are doing this for. We believe that local production is critical to allow local communities to thrive, and we want to do all that we can to help the planet survive the global challenges we face.

Value proposition – what we do today

Gelato connects global creators with the best local makers through industry-leading software so everyone can conduct worldwide business where products are made better, produced closer and delivered faster, with fewer emissions, to customers anywhere.

Stakeholders – who we exist for

We have three primary stakeholders – our people, our customers and our shareholders.

How we balance these interests is crucial to the ethos we are building at Gelato. We are clear that we are in this for the long term and are led by our mission. We believe that by:

1.attracting and enabling the best people, we will
2.deliver unfairly good experiences for our customers, and that in turn will
3.make our shareholders successful.

In short: 🧑‍💻 → 🙌 → 📈

📖 Gelato handbook / 💜 Principles

Principles

Our principles set the standard for how we work together.

When you join Gelato, you commit to living these principles and embracing the trade-offs they ask of us. Doing so isn’t optional – it’s part of how high performance here is defined (→ Performance playbook).

In return, you will thrive here. And so will the team.

This page shows our Principles as a simple, practical cheat sheet for how to operate. This lets us:

  1. operate as one team with one operating system
  2. move faster with fewer misalignments and less friction
  3. deliver consistent, high-quality results

Our Cultural Anchors

Culture Deck: Our beliefs, philosophy, and the why behind.

How We Work @ Gelato: The lived experience – narrative, recruiting, and what it feels like to be here.

Principles: Clear behavioral standards – what to do, how to act, how to decide.

Together, these define our operating system: how we lead, collaborate, move fast, and scale without complexity.

In a nutshell

We chase outsized impact with a lean-team mindset: high intensity, sharp focus, and exceptional craft.

We automate the busywork and speak hard truths with respect. No ego, no drama – just forward motion.

If you love shipping fast, learning faster, and taking on “impossible” challenges together, you will thrive at Gelato.

In detail

The following pages present each principle in depth, including:

  • Definition
  • What good looks like and what it doesn’t look like
  • Expected outcomes if applied consistently
  • Trade-offs
  • Connection to Culture Deck and Booklist
  • When principles conflict
1 Think As One Team ▾
Team before ego. Debate ideas openly, decide clearly, then move as one.
Culture Deck: “We battle over ideas while we forget our titles. The best idea wins.”
“We prioritize the collective rather than the individual.”
● This looks like
  • Saying “I disagree because…” in the meeting, not afterwards
  • Asking “What am I missing?” before defending your view
  • Giving feedback directly, not through side channels
  • Helping another team win, even if it’s not your task
  • Once a decision is made, committing fully, even if you argued the opposite
  • Knowing when to debate and when to defer. If it’s your domain, you decide after gathering input. If it’s someone else’s domain, you give input, then support their call
● This doesn’t look like
  • Staying silent in the room, then complaining offline
  • Escalating by CC’ing managers instead of resolving directly
  • Saying “That’s not my/my team’s job”
  • Agreeing publicly, then resisting or slowing things down afterwards
If we do this
The best ideas win. We move faster. Trust strengthens.
In exchange, we trade off
This is not a place for people who need hierarchy, prefer consensus over clarity, or keep opinions to themselves. We choose speed, honesty, and ownership over comfort.
Learn from
Radical Candor, Kim Scott
Leaders Eat Last, Simon Sinek
The Five Dysfunctions of a Team, Patrick Lencioni
2 Move Fast, Stay Calm ▾
We move at high velocity and change until we win – treating setbacks as data, not drama. Calm mind and focus are what sustain the pace.
Culture Deck: “It’s not the big that eats the small; it’s the fast that eats the slow.”
“Those who can’t change their minds can’t change anything.”
“Deadlines bring discipline and focus… perfection doesn’t exist.”
● This looks like
  • Deciding with ~70% of the information
  • Saying “Let’s test it” instead of debating hypotheticals
  • Asking “How do we fix it?” before “Who caused it?”
  • Changing direction when the data emerges, without ego
  • Saying no to low-impact work so you can deliver what matters
  • Responding, not reacting
  • Keeping your team steady. If you’re a leader, your energy sets the tone. If you panic, they panic
● This doesn’t look like
  • Sending late-night messages about non-urgent things
  • Treating every issue like a five-alarm fire
  • Sending all-caps messages or panic pings
  • Confusing urgency with anxiety
  • Sticking to a plan just because “we already decided”
  • Cutting corners and calling it speed
  • Waiting for permission when you know the right next step
  • Saying yes to everything and completing nothing
If we do this
We take more shots, learn faster, and stay ahead.
In exchange, we trade off
Perfectionism doesn’t survive here. Neither does fear of being wrong. If you need certainty before acting, or stability to feel secure, this pace will be hard.
Learn from
Thinking, Fast and Slow, Daniel Kahneman
Essentialism, Greg McKeown
Black Box Thinking, Matthew Syed
3 Be AI-First ▾
We use AI to amplify our impact – automate the routine, accelerate the complex, and focus human energy where it matters most.
Culture Deck: “Innovation has always been the core of Gelato.”
“Our company’s competitiveness is propelled by the search for and implementation of new technologies.”
● This looks like
  • Asking “How can AI do this?” before you start
  • Using AI to learn faster and raise the quality of your decisions
  • Designing workflows that are AI-native, not AI-patched
  • Staying curious and experimenting with new capabilities
  • Knowing where AI creates the most leverage in your role, and focusing there first
  • Sharing what works so the team gets better, not just you
  • Knowing when AI isn’t enough. Use AI, but you still own the thinking, the relationships, and the final call
● This doesn’t look like
  • Doing manually what could be automated
  • Treating AI as a threat instead of a force multiplier
  • Waiting for someone else to figure out how AI applies to your work
  • Blindly trusting AI outputs without validating them
  • Using AI as an excuse for lazy thinking
  • Saying “We’ve always done it this way”
  • Keeping effective AI workflows to yourself
If we do this
We scale faster, innovate sharper, and do more with less – freeing ourselves for the work that actually requires judgment, creativity, and leadership.
In exchange, we trade off
Manual comfort zones and static workflows. If you resist new tools and ways of working, expect your role to stay the same – you will fall behind.
Learn from
The Innovator’s Dilemma, Clayton Christensen
The AI Driven Leader, Geoff Woods
4 Take Ownership ▾
We own outcomes, not tasks. When something needs fixing, we fix it – or get it fixed. No waiting, no excuses.
Culture Deck: “Discipline, Details, and Deadlines – all three sit at the heart of how we operate.”
“If you make a mistake – raise your hand and say, ‘I am sorry, but I made a mistake’.”
“If you need help – raise your hand and say – I need help”
● This looks like
  • Following through until the work is truly done, not just handed off
  • Saying “I’ll make sure it happens” and meaning it
  • Naming your mistake before someone else finds it
  • Treating company resources like your own money
  • Solving problems that aren’t technically your job but are in your path
  • Holding yourself to a high standard of craft—even under time pressure
  • Asking for help, getting it done matters more than looking like you have it handled
  • Escalating when you’re blocked, but only after you’ve tried to solve it
● This doesn’t look like
  • “I sent the email” (but didn’t follow up)
  • “That’s not my responsibility”
  • Waiting to be told what to do
  • Blaming circumstances, other teams, or lack of resources
  • Taking credit for the win but not the miss
  • Struggling alone because asking for help feels like failure
If we do this
We earn trust, compound results, and build a company that lasts. People can rely on each other because commitments mean something.
In exchange, we trade off
Excuses and passivity. If you need to be told what to do, prefer narrow task ownership, or avoid accountability – this environment will feel uncomfortable.
Learn from
Extreme Ownership, Jocko Willink
The Hard Thing About Hard Things, Ben Horowitz
Shoe Dog, Phil Knight
5 Own Your Growth ▾
Growth is self-driven. We learn from the best, seek feedback early, and raise the bar – for ourselves and each other.
Culture Deck: “It’s the attitude that creates a winner. An attitude that’s constantly pushing towards learning and acquiring new skills.”
“If you are to grow an apple tree, start by reading a summary written by ‘the world champion’.”
● This looks like
  • Seeking feedback before it’s given – from peers, managers, and direct reports
  • Learning from the best in your field, inside or outside Gelato
  • Taking on hard problems that stretch you, not just tasks you’ve mastered
  • Sharing what you’ve learned so the team grows with you
  • Separating the work from your identity. Feedback on your output isn’t a judgment of your worth. It’s data to get better
● This doesn’t look like
  • Waiting for a course or formal training to develop
  • Getting defensive when someone points out a gap
  • Dismissing feedback because of who it came from
  • Coasting on what got you here
  • Treating feedback as a personal attack
  • Growing only when it feels convenient
If we do this
We get better individually and collectively. Our work sets a new standard – and the bar keeps rising.
In exchange, we trade off
Staying still. The bar at Gelato is high, and it keeps moving. It can be hard to switch off – growth takes energy.
Learn from
Grit, Angela Duckworth
Great by Choice, Jim Collins
Black Box Thinking, Matthew Syed
6 Serve The Customer ▾
We exist to make our customers successful. Every decision, feature, and process should ladder up to customer value, not just internal convenience.
Culture Deck: “We end our culture deck with the most important thing. What brings us to dance and whose success is crucial for our ability to succeed: our customers.”
● This looks like
  • Asking “How does this help the customer?” before building anything
  • Choosing customer impact over internal perfection
  • Listening to customer feedback, and acting on it fast
  • Treating customer escalations as urgent, even if they’re inconvenient
  • Saying no to features that don’t move the needle for customers
  • Putting yourself in the customer’s shoes: if this happened to you, would you be happy?
● This doesn’t look like
  • Building what’s easy for us, not what’s valuable for them
  • Ignoring customer pain because “it’s not our team’s job”
  • Treating customers like tickets, not people
  • Shipping something and moving on without checking if it worked
  • Prioritizing internal projects over customer needs
If we do this
Customers trust us, renew, and refer others. Our growth compounds.
In exchange, we trade off
Internal convenience and pet projects. If it doesn’t serve the customer, it doesn’t ship.
Learn from
The Everything Store, Brad Stone, Jeff Bezos / Amazon
Delivering Happiness, Tony Hsieh, Zappos

As Gelato Team Member you can expense a copy (physical, eBook, audiobook) of each book from our booklist.

In practice

Our six principles will sometimes pull in different directions: speed vs. calm, ownership vs. collaboration, innovation vs. focus.

That tension is intentional. Great teams don’t avoid it. They use clarity, feedback, and shared intent to find the right path forward.

Think of it like this:

  1. Each principle has an equal seat at the table.
  2. Together, they help us see the full problem – not just one angle.
  3. Our rituals and ways of working guide us to the right balance for the situation.

House rules – we do not accept:

Relying on lazy trade-offs
It’s easy to say, “We can’t do X and Y at the same time.”
But the best teams break those assumptions.
Example: you can ship fast and maintain high quality – with clear requirements, small scope, rapid feedback, and iteration.
Our principles are here to help us find smarter paths, not excuses.
Weaponizing principles for personal gain
Principles help us succeed as a team, not win arguments or justify poor work.
Example: delivering low-quality output and defending it with, “I move fast,” is not living the principle.
Likewise, if another team seems slow, don’t gossip or escalate – give direct feedback and help them improve.
Principles guide behavior; they are not shields or weapons.

When principles conflict with each other

Principle Resolution
Think as One Team If debate is slowing progress → timebox, decide, ship (Move Fast, Stay Focused)
If you disagree with a final call → commit fully; revisit only with new data
If someone isn’t hearing your challenge → try once with clearer framing, then escalate with them, not around them
Move Fast, Stay Calm If speed is breaking trust → slow down just enough to bring others with you (Think as One Team)
If quality is slipping → reduce scope, never standards (Take Ownership)
If constant pivots mean nothing ships → finish one thing before switching, or ask for help (Take Ownership)
Be AI-First If AI speeds you up but quality drops → you still own the output; AI is an assistant, not a replacement (Take Ownership)
If AI adoption leaves teammates behind → bring them with you; share what you learn (Think as One Team)
If you’re automating before understanding → slow down; learn the process before optimizing (Own Your Growth)
Take Ownership If ownership pulls you into another team’s territory → loop them in and solve it together (Think as One Team)
If you’re waiting for perfect information → make the call and own it (Move Fast, Stay Calm)
If owning the process means doing it manually when AI could do it better → own the outcome, not the method (Be AI-First)
Own Your Growth If learning slows delivery → timebox; learn by shipping, not by studying forever (Move Fast, Stay Calm)
If you’re growing alone → bring others with you; teach what you learn (Think as One Team)
If feedback feels personal → separate the work from your identity; growth requires honesty (Think as One Team)
Serve The Customer If customer requests conflict with speed → clarify priorities with them; ship what matters most first (Move Fast, Stay Calm)
If serving one customer hurts the product for others → optimize for the many, not the one (Think as One Team)
If a customer asks for something we can’t sustain → be honest and offer alternatives (Take Ownership)
📖 Gelato handbook / 🤖 AI at Gelato

AI at Gelato

AI is for us and by us. We should all have a say in what we use and how.

We believe AI and automation technologies should be leveraged responsibly, ethically, and equitably wherever possible to augment and empower Team Members, not replace them.

We will design and use AI capabilities with the following principles in mind:

1. We’re in charge of the tools we use – and accountable for them.

We decide when and where to deploy AI – and we’re accountable for the outcomes, whether the work is done by us or by AI. AI can act, not just recommend. But even when we delegate tasks to AI, we’re responsible for the decisions and impact. That’s why Team Members are at the start and end of AI: we initiate it, and we own what happens next – for our people, our customers, and our stakeholders.

2. We collaborate with AI, not compete with it – so we can move fast and stay lean.

We use AI to handle routine tasks and to supercharge complex, high-value work – from deep research to high-level analysis. This frees us to focus on uniquely human strengths like critical thinking, judgement, and meaningful interaction with customers and candidates.

3. We experiment responsibly.

AI is evolving fast, and so are we. We test and adopt new tools with curiosity, but also with care. We use AI in ways that comply with laws on data protection, confidentiality, and intellectual property; not in spite of them. We monitor both the benefits and unintended consequences of these tools, and we adapt based on what we learn.

4. We educate ourselves and each other.

As tasks evolve and new tools emerge, the skills each role needs will change too. But Team Members are – and always will be – at the heart of Gelato’s success. We’re committed to re-training and up-skilling, not just to adapt, but to unlock new ways of working. We’ll share what’s working across the business so others can build on it. And we’ll support experimentation that helps everyone level up with AI.

5. We make AI fair and accessible to everyone.

We evaluate AI systems for bias and make adjustments to prevent discriminatory treatment before deployment. AI must be designed and used to make fair, unbiased, and equitable decisions and recommendations for all people.

📖 Gelato handbook / 🎯 Performance playbook

Performance playbook

Expectations at Gelato are high – and that’s a good thing. To meet them, we need to hold ourselves and each other to account.

This playbook exists to make that possible: it brings clarity to how we define performance, how we talk about it, and how we support each other to raise the bar.

Table of contents
  • How do we define + measure performance?
  • How do we enable exceptional performance?
  • ⛽ OILS checks
  • 🔭 Performance Development Dialogues
  • How does performance link to pay & promotions?

Who does what?

RoleResponsibilityWho
DriverGives continuous feedback and sets future goalsPeople Leaders (PL)
ApproverSets targets + decides what goes into the performance playbookLeadership Team (LT)
Contributor(s)Gives input on performance management as neededPeople & Talent (P&T)
InformedReceives feedback + self-reflects; gives upward/peer feedbackTeam Member (TM)

How do we define + measure performance?

Performance = how consistently you meet or raise our (high) expectations, across 3 dimensions.

DimensionThis covers...Ask yourself:
Results Your ability to deliver high-quality work against goals, OKRs, or team priorities. → What targets have you met (quota, roadmap, OKRs, projects, KPIs, etc.)?
→ How fast + reliably do you deliver, and what’s the quality?
Skills The human + technical capabilities that help you succeed in your role, as outlined in JDs → How well do you fulfill the mission and responsibilities in your JD? What is the 20% of tasks that will drive 80% of results? What can be automated?
Culture The way you live our Principles, and positively contribute to the team and company. → How did you observably demonstrate our valued behaviours in your work or with your team?

Throughout your time at Gelato, you will move between 3 states:

StateThat means...On average, we expect that:
⭐ Above & beyond You consistently exceed expectations and create impact beyond your core job, in ways that raise the bar for others. ~5–10% of TMs are in this state at any given time
🟢 Right on track You reliably meet + sometimes exceed our (high) expectations. ~80–85% of TMs are in this state at any given time
🔶 Let’s adjust You’re not meeting some expectations + should course-correct; this is a chance to realign and reset. ~10% of TMs are in this state at any given time

How do we set targets?

Gelato’s leadership team (LT; see here) sets our strategy every 12 months as part of the yearly OKR setting cycle.

The yearly OKRs are further broken down to quarterly OKRs ahead of the start of the next quarter.

That plan is further broken down into team-level goals, such as 6-monthly roadmaps (PDE, People & Talent) and monthly/quarterly quotas (GTM).

This way, every TM and team knows what they are expected to deliver.

How do we enable exceptional performance?

We have 2 rituals to enable all TMs to talk about performance continuously. Both rituals serve to help you understand how you’re doing and what to focus on next:

RitualCadenceWhat it isWhat it’s meant for
OILS check Monthly Recap how the month has gone (OILS format) + what to do next A lightweight touchpoint to build feedback muscle
Perf Dev Dialogues 6-monthly Look ahead what great looks like in 6 months + how to get there Checkpoint on your career path + how you’re tracking there

⛽ OILS checks

An OILS check is...

A monthly recap – what stood out performance-wise – that serves as the basis for a meaningful two-way discussion, and at least 1 concrete takeaway to put into action until next time. Goals are:

  1. Give feedback what stood out in your performance from a results / skills / culture view
  2. Have healthy, unfiltered conversation on that feedback (e.g. where do you (dis)agree and why?)
  3. End on a concrete, actionable suggestion on what to tweak for the coming month

Every PL is trained on + recommended to give feedback using the OILS format (Observation, Impact, Listen, Suggestion) – hence the name.

A great OILS check looks like...

  1. Feedback on at least 2 out of 3 performance dimensions
  2. In OILS format (or another structured feedback framework that you + your PL agree on)
  3. An indicator to help you understand if you’ve gone ⭐ above & beyond, are 🟢 right on track, or should 🔶 adjust
  4. At least 1 concrete action item to work on (no matter how bite-sized)

OILS checks should be documented...

In Leapsome – once per month you will receive task from Leapsome to complete OILS check form (60–90 seconds to fill)

Date

Dimensions covered (requirement: ≥2, matching “great OILS.”)

  • Results
  • Skills
  • Culture

Indicator (⭐ / 🟢 / 🔶)

Key observation (1–2 bullets max)

Agreed next action (1 bullet, owner + due date) – required.

(Optional but powerful) Team Member reaction (one sentence: agree/disagree/why) to cover the “Listen” part without forcing essays.

Hard rule: no narrative paragraphs. Bullets only.

  • Click here to see examples of a filled-out OILS table.
  • We also made a custom GPT called Gelato OILS Coach to help turn feedback into OILS format.

🔭 Performance Development Dialogues

A performance development dialogue is...

A 6-month coaching conversation to define what “great” looks like in your role going forward + how to close the gap.

Everyone with a minimum 6 months tenure and not on a recovery plan is included in the cycle. It’s forward-looking, practical, and anchored in feedback you’ve already received. There’s 4 input fields:

Input fieldKey question🔄 Self⬇️ Manager
Future growthIn 6 months, what would great look like in this role?✔️✔️
Today’s stateWhere are you/they now compared to that?✔️✔️
Closing the gapWhat would help you/them get from here to there?✔️✔️
IndicatorHow are you/they doing right now? (⭐ / 🟢 / 🔶)✔️✔️

Coaching depends on where + how big the gap is:

StateCoaching focus
⭐ Accelerating aheadChallenge: Focus on ways in which you can up your contribution to Gelato (e.g. scope, level) and role-model our valued behaviors.
🟢 Progressing steadilyEmpower: Take growth opportunities that allow you to stretch your skills and demonstrate exceptional performance.
🔶 Re-orientingRecover: Focus on areas of improvement, working closely with your PL to close gaps.

A great performance development dialogue looks like...

  1. No surprises – all feedback should have been given in the last 6 months in OILS checks
  2. Focus on practical coaching by creating an action plan for the next 6 months

Performance development dialogue should be documented...

In Leapsome, driven by the People team.

Each cycle runs for 2–3 weeks:

Step 1🔄 Everyone fills out their self-reflections
Step 2⬇️ PL share their reflections with direct reports
Step 3👥 PL commit to goals with their direct reports

What about giving/receiving peer or upward feedback?

While they’re not part of our company-level rituals right now, we encourage everyone to bake mutual feedback into their team rituals (retrospectives, team meetings, etc.).

Ask the P&T if you want help running a peer or upward review – we can easily set it up in Leapsome.

How does performance link to pay & promotions?

Doing great work consistently puts you in the best position to progress quickly and earn more – we’ll always out-reward out-performance.

Every 6 months, performance development dialogues are your opportunity to have a transparent, forward-looking conversation about your path – including pay and promotion.

That said, performance isn’t mechanically linked to pay or progression. For example:

  • Being in ⭐️-state 3 months in a row doesn’t automatically mean a promotion or pay rise. Those decisions depend on more than just individual performance – like team needs, business performance, and timing.
  • Being in 🔶-state 3 months in a row doesn’t automatically trigger a formal recovery process. Underperformance is handled case-by-case, and formal processes only kick in if it’s serious and sustained

Performance is how you meet the expectations of the work you’re paid for. This makes performance a necessary input into pay (but not sufficient on its own).

Pay...Performance...
is a reflection of external marketsis an internal, company-specific measure
is steady for longer periods of timefluctuates day-to-day
is usually irreversible (doesn’t go down)can go up or down (even if pay only goes up)
is something you get from your employeris something you give to your employer

Due to this, we make no explicit link between performance categories and pay in this framework iteration. That means being in the “exceptional” category does not automatically mean a raise.

Pay and company performance

Even someone who consistently delivers exceptional performance might not get a pay increase if the company’s financial position doesn’t allow it. That’s because increases are contingent on us meeting key financial goals.

If we don’t hit our targets, we have to adjust our budget to keep Gelato healthy and sustainable.

Questions

Got a question or something unclear? Ask your PL or drop a note to hr@gelato.com
📖 Gelato handbook / 🔍 Focus playbook

Focus playbook

We can do anything, but not everything. We must focus to deliver results. Focus means knowing:

  1. what we’re supposed to deliver
  2. why that makes Gelato successful
  3. how we spend our time and energy to get there

Below are the best practices we encourage team members to follow in order to achieve this.

ResourceUse for
Meetings framework & templates → Triaging what should be a meeting at all
→ Template for good meetings and 121s
→ How to say no to a meeting

Deep Work Wednesday

Wednesdays are designated days at Gelato without internal meetings. Use this time to focus on deep work without interruption. Exceptions only if:

  • All parties agree to have the meeting (e.g. something urgent + important)
  • It’s an onboarding session
  • It’s an interview

Please keep Slack noise to a minimum as it can be just as disruptive as a meeting.

📖 Gelato handbook / 🔍 Focus playbook / 📅 Meetings framework & templates

Meetings framework & templates

Use for...
→ Triaging what should be a meeting at all
→ Template for good meetings and 121s
→ How to say no to a meeting

Meetings are often seen as keeping you from doing work when they should enable you to do more focused work.

This page defines what kind of meeting creates focus at Gelato and what a well-run meeting looks like.

Note: This guide excludes agile meetings and ceremonies, which follow a specific methodology.

How you can proactively make meetings better today

  1. Check if your meetings fit into at least one of the categories; if not, can it be async?
  2. Check that the meetings you’re in are up to PAR; if not, challenge directly next time.
  3. If (1)+(2) are OK, take a few minutes to discuss together if you could make it more efficient in other ways, e.g. making it shorter or less frequent.

What are (good) meetings good for?

Your time is the most valuable resource you have. Good meetings respect that resource by enabling focused work, not disrupting it.

✅ Should be a meeting

Should be a meetingBecause it...Example
Making big-impact decisionsunblocks focused workProduct roadmap trade-offs
Discussing ideas and issues collaborativelycreates clarityWorkshops, AMAs, pitch day
Energising others through storytellingmotivatesAll-hands
Aligning on key prioritieshelps prioritise workOffsites
Coaching, enabling and giving feedbackhelps do better work121s, retros, career development

🟡 Depends on your/their work style

Should be a meetingBecause it...Example
Spontaneous huddles to resolve small issuesis faster to just talkAnything that takes <5min to resolve

❌ Shouldn’t be a meeting, make it async

Shouldn’t be a meetingBecause it...Example
Making low-impact decisionstakes up more time than it savesGetting a new coffee machine
Sharing information with no extra value addA really boring all-hands
Giving one-way updates (no back-and-forth)“This could’ve been an email” syncs

What does a good meeting look like?

RecommendationAreaKey questionTips
Every meeting should be up to PAR – purpose, agenda, results Agenda What about? → Good meetings are often ruined by terrible prep
→ Everyone in the meeting is in charge of the cost of that use of time; if it’s not up to PAR, healthily challenge the owner
Make it uncomfortably short. Duration How long? → People tend to go on for as long as the meeting is scheduled
→ Experiment with 15 vs 30min
→ Call it as a win if you end 5–10min early
Make it uncomfortably small. Participants Who with? → Who do you absolutely need to make the decision / discuss the issue / hear what you have to say?
→ There should never be optional attendees
Cluster it with other meetings you/others already have. Timing When in the week? → Cluster your own meetings to reduce context-switching
→ Look at others calendars first
→ Don’t put it on Wednesdays, those are for deep work
Schedule a recurring meeting for 4 instances, then re-assess. Frequency How often? → Recurring meetings are often forever by default when they should be on a trial basis
→ Once over, ask “does this warrant [ ] h per week indefinitely”

Templates

Copy-paste the recommended template below into any recurring meetings doc you have or use it as a basis for any one-off meeting:

“Classic” meetings

⭐ PAR

Timekeeper: [select one person that holds the group accountable to time]

  • Purpose: [1 sentence what this meeting is for]
  • Agenda: [Add each item and how long you expect it to take]
  • Results: [What would a successful end to the meeting be?]

📖 Pre-reads

  • [Circulate at least 24h before]
  • [Let participants know how long you expect this to take – i.e. 8 min read]

✍️ Notes

Notetaker: [select one person that ensures everything important is written down]

Agenda itemNotesNext steps
   
  • [Add whatever you need – links, writing, images etc.]
  • [Don’t meticulously write down anything that’s said – nobody re-reads these anyway and it’s distracting. Opt for a recording instead if anyone can’t make it]

☑️ Action points

What did we decide? Who needs to do what by when? Who else needs to know?

  • [Write as “@person to do X by DATE” – it’s the person’s responsibility to capture the action in their to-do list]

How to say ‘no’ to a meeting

What you / others are comfortable saying will depend on personality, previous experiences, ways of working, culture etc.

Meetings that...How to hold each other accountableWhat to say
are not up to standard Challenge the PAR “I can’t see an agenda, outcomes or pre-read in the invite / Notion doc. Can you share them please so I can prepare?”
could be async Challenge the ninja “Looking at the agenda I’m wondering if we can resolve this async. Are you OK to share a [Loom/message] instead?”
you don’t need to be in Challenge the list “Looking at the agenda I’m wondering if I am needed to [align on this / make this decision / ...]. Can you clarify how I can add value?”
conflict with your priorities Say no by saying yes “I am a bit overloaded with meetings lately and I really want to free up my time to focus on [my priorities]. Can we postpone until [ ]?”
de-rail from the agenda Assign a time-keeper “Who is going to make sure we stick to time/topic?”

People leader playbook

To help make people leaders at Gelato more successful, by:

  1. Being clear about what Gelato expects of a people leader
  2. Giving people leaders the tools that enable them to succeed

Performance is assessed in line with Gelato’s Performance playbook.

Who reviews this playbook and how often?

This playbook is refined continuously. We use the DACI framework to clarify who does what:

RoleResponsibilityWho
DriverDrives the playbook forward and decides new contentP&T (People & Talent)
ApproverSigns off on important new content (in limited cases)LT (Leadership Team)
Contributor(s)Generates or is asked for input on contentP&T + PLs (People Leaders)
InformedIs kept in the loop about new content and progressPLs

Mission & expectations

What is a people leader?

Anyone who has at least one direct report in our org chart.

All PLs come together as a community in the monthly People Leader’s All Hands.

Why do people leaders exist at Gelato?

To make their team(s) successful by:

AreaDefinition
Delivering results...as defined in the masterplan / roadmaps / OKRs
Creating clarity...on what is expected through ongoing performance conversations
Generating energy...through day-to-day enablement and long-term career development

What is expected of people leaders at Gelato?

People leader expectations are evaluated in 6-monthly performance development dialogues. Each job description has 2 sets of expectations:

  1. Expectations that are specific to the people leader’s role, team, function etc.
  2. Expectations that are the same for every people leader

Core expectations that are the same for every people leader are:

ExpectationResponsibilitiesOutcomes
Drive results → Set the right context for direct reports (DRs) to perform
→ Manage performance for your team and part of the business that you are responsible for, proactively inform and escalate concerns to your LT member
→ Act as hiring people leader for new roles in your team (for Recruitment related topics, go to Recruitment Wiki)		 Team(s) hit(s) targets
Create clarity → Write onboarding plans
→ Drive expected regular meetings (PDD, 121s)
→ Report and give visibility on team performance to the team and to your LT member		 DRs have regular 121s, 6-monthly retros and career development sessions (=Performance Development Dialogues)
Generate energy → Match work to your DRs’ strengths and career growth areas where possible
→ Make sure your DRs are engaged (through team meetups, socials, actions from pulse surveys)
→ Ensure DRs take time off regularly to avoid bottlenecks		 Team eNPS is >60

Key growth opportunities for people leaders

(as delegated by their LT member) are:

More input on the masterplan

  • Set new strategic goals for direct reports
  • Make recommendations on team structure
  • Make headcount plans or decide to fire

More autonomy over employee relations

  • Make decisions on pay rises
  • Create career maps or job descriptions

People leaders should not go solo on cross-functional issues, such as:

Big budget decisions (→ involve Finance)

  • Approve large expenses or accounts

Complex HR cases (→ involve People & Talent)

  • Resolve HR concerns or issues alone

Legal/compliance risks (→ involve Legal)

  • Resolve anything legal-related alone

How to give/get great feedback

Topic: Performance

Why do we have this?

Giving feedback and challenging directly is part of our Principles. This guide walks you through our recommended way to give great feedback: the OILS framework.

Great feedback happens naturally and is:
  1. Constructive = energises you to improve
  2. Structured = gives clarity how to do that
  3. Timely = help get results quickly

Official touchpoints for feedback:
  • Peer and manager feedback during month 3 of onboarding (→ Onboarding)
  • Monthly OIL checks (→ Performance playbook)

Why does feedback matter?

Great feedback helps people become high performers by:

  • Building trust through open, candid 2-way dialogue
  • Addressing and solving problems directly (vs bad surprises in performance development dialogues later)
  • Uncovering blind spots by validating and aligning different viewpoints
  • Enabling personal and professional development
  • Reinforcing standards of excellence
Here are short summaries of Radical Candor, one of the books from our Book List, specifically on feedback culture:

Radical Candor Graphic Summary
Radical Candor Text Summary

But companies struggle with this:

  • 74% of employees leave their performance development conversations or 121s unsure of what their managers actually think of their performance.
  • 72% of people feel their performance would improve if their managers gave corrective feedback.

What can go wrong with feedback?

Without the right context, feedback can be misinterpreted. In other words, what one person says and what those words mean to another person can be different. For example:

What is saidWhat it could mean
You and your partner are in the car waiting at a red light. As the light turns green, your partner says:

🚦 “The light is green.”		 Factual statement / observation:
“The colour of the traffic light is green.”
Appeal to action:
“Step on the gas, slowpoke!”
Support:
“I want to help you by telling you this.”
Self-disclosure:
“I’m impatient and don’t like waiting.”

Miscommunicated feedback leads to:

  • Defensiveness
  • Loss of confidence
  • Disengagement (problem driven vs solutions)
  • Focusing on the wrong thing / wasting time
  • Undermines trust

How do we give & take feedback (OILS)?

It is up to managers to agree with their teams how and when to give/receive feedback. We recommend using the framework below as a way to put great feedback in practice:

StepWhatHow
Observation Describe the specific behaviour or situation you observed “When you [did X]...”
Impact Explain the effect it had “...the impact was [Y]”
Listen Ask for their perspective “What do you think?”
Suggestion Offer a concrete next step “It would be great if you could [Z]”

Here is how you could add OILS feedback to your regular 121 documentation:

FromOILS
Thomas → Richard When you delivered today’s training, you came across very natural and answered questions with candour. → Makes MNs eager for more
→ Helps MNs improve

🟢 Right on track		 What do you think, Richard?

→ [...]		 Would be excellent to teach People Leaders on how to deliver great training like this.

When should you give & ask for feedback?

Here is how you can decide when to give feedback:

Type of feedbackUsed forExamplesEmotional hurdleWhen to give feedback
Technical instruction (TI) → Course corrections
→ Small changes to a task or piece of work		 → When a report is missing details
→ When a message could be written more concisely

This often looks like “Thanks for sharing [ ] – can you please change/add [ ]?”		 Low Immediately / in the moment
Performance feedback (PF) → Ways of working (e.g. behaviour)
→ After providing repeated TIs		 → When somebody is routinely late to team meetings
→ When the same piece of TI has been given multiple times		 Medium to high In 121s

Best practices for feedback

WhatHowExample
Do it early, do it often. → Make it a habit of your 121s
→ Schedule time to debrief after e.g. a presentation		 Mutual feedback section in 121s
Do it in (virtual) person. → Giving: sync, e.g. at the next 121 – async risks loss of context
→ Asking: sync or async (e.g. over Slack)		 “In our next 121 / retro, I’d like to give you / ask you for feedback on...”
Do it after specific instances. → Giving: after observing concrete examples
→ Asking: pose specific questions vs general “how did I do”		 “What could I improve in my presentation style / slide content”

What if someone gets defensive?

When encountering a tricky challenge, first identify whether it is truly difficult or just unpleasant to guide your approach:

  • Difficult problems are those that require intensive resources, time, and attention to solve
  • Unpleasant problems have a more obvious answer but we’re still reluctant to tackle them

For example, rooting out a breakdown in a process might be a difficult problem, while giving tough performance feedback to a TM could be an unpleasant one.

If someone gets defensive during feedback:

What to doWhat to say
Pause the conversation“Let’s take a moment here”
Reinforce positive intent“I’m sharing this to help you succeed”
Acknowledge emotions“I can see this is triggering strong feelings”
Offer space“We can continue now or pause and resume later”
📖 Gelato handbook / 📋 People leader playbook / 📚 Team member development

Team member development @ Gelato

We believe people grow best when allowed to develop themselves – by working alongside exceptional colleagues and tackling ambitious challenges.

Formalized development methods – such as courses, rotational programs, or rigid career paths – have their place in a learning model but are often less effective in a fast-paced environment like ours where the key is to stay agile.

Instead, we trust in the self-driven nature of high-performing individuals. They evolve through experience, reflection, observation, reading, and meaningful conversations – provided they’re supported by great teammates and real challenges.

The 70-20-10 model

At Gelato, we believe in the 70-20-10 model:

SplitSourceDetails
70% On-the-job experiences Learning through practical, hands-on work and solving real-life problems. Team members gain skills by taking on new challenges, making decisions, and reflecting on their work.
20% Social interactions Learning through feedback, collaboration, and observing others. Coaching, networking, book club discussions, and working with colleagues play a key role here.
10% Formal education Structured courses, workshops, seminars, and other traditional forms of instruction. Books, e-learning programs, conferences & classroom training are examples of formal learning opportunities.

If formal education is justified and supported by a business case, the process for applying is described here.

Roles & responsibilities

Team member ownedLeader facilitatedGelato supported
Take charge of your own development and career Take time with team members to discuss their career aspirations Communicate future direction and skills requirements
Close the skill gap for current and future positions Listen and provide feedback, ideas, and contacts Provide information and tools when applicable
Seize development and stretch opportunities Make choices to support their development Communicate internal opportunities
📖 Gelato handbook / 📋 People leader playbook / 🧠 Leadership frameworks & tools

Leadership frameworks & tools

As a people leader at Gelato, you are expected to act as a coach, mentor, and role model – and to cultivate an environment led by trust, authenticity, predictability, and a healthy failing culture.

To help you do this consistently, we lead our teams through the lens of the following frameworks. They help us maintain a culture of open and transparent communication which enables our teams to grow and collaborate more effectively.

Our frameworks

FrameworkPurposeApplication
Situational Leadership (SL) Helps you analyze and understand a team member’s current abilities and the specific needs of a situation. Assess each team member’s competence and commitment regarding a specific task. Adapt your leadership style (Telling, Selling, Participating, Delegating) based on their readiness level.
OILS (Observation, Impact, Listen, Suggestion) Gelato’s structured format for delivering feedback that is clear, specific, and actionable. When there is a mismatch in SL between the leader’s style and team member’s readiness level, use OILS to give specific, consistent feedback. Describe what you observed, explain the impact, listen to the other person’s perspective, and co-create a suggestion for next steps. Works in any setting – from monthly check-ins to spontaneous conversations. → How to give/get great feedback
Radical Candor Promotes an open communication culture where feedback is given with care and directness. Integrate Radical Candor principles by showing personal care while challenging directly. Use this approach alongside OILS to ensure feedback is delivered compassionately yet effectively, fostering trust and psychological safety.
Team Management Profile (TMP) Enhances understanding of individual work preferences and how these influence team dynamics. Tailor your communication and feedback (using OILS) according to TMP insights. Understand each team member’s preferred way of working and use this knowledge to foster better collaboration and conflict resolution.
Myers-Briggs Type Indicator (MBTI) Offers insights into personality types and preferences, aiding in better understanding and communication within the team. Leverage MBTI to customize your leadership approach. Recognize different personality traits and adjust your interactions and feedback methods to align with each team member’s preferences.
5 Dysfunctions of a Team Identifies common pitfalls that hinder team performance and cohesion. Recognize and address dysfunctions: Absence of Trust, Fear of Conflict, Lack of Commitment, Avoidance of Accountability, Inattention to Results. Use team-building exercises, open communication, and clear goal-setting to overcome these dysfunctions and build a more cohesive and effective team.

Go deeper

Explore resources to deepen your understanding of each framework:

  • Situational Leadership – LMS course
  • OILS – How to give/get great feedback
  • Radical Candor – Summary (graphic) · Summary (text)
  • Team Management Profile (TMP) – LMS course
  • Myers-Briggs Type Indicator (MBTI) – LMS course
  • 5 Dysfunctions of a Team – LMS course
